            <biogHist>
                <p>Duncan Whyte was born on 22 October 1805 in Lorn Furnace, or Bonawe Furnace, a
                    small industrial settlement just outside Taynuilt, Argyll. His father was
                    William Whyte, and is listed on the birth record as a carpenter, possibly at the
                    large ironworks there, though Duncan's death record has him as a postmaster; his
                    mother was Catherine Whyte née Campbell.</p>
                <p>In 1834 Duncan, now living in Oban, married Jean Whyte née Stevenson, a
                    shoemaker's daughter from Kilmarnock. By 1851 they were living at 7 Combie
                    Street, Oban, presumably above Duncan's shop, with no less than seven young
                    children and a servant. After then, the family appears to have flitted around
                    the town, first to another property on Crombie Street, then around several
                    locations on the town's George Street. Duncan was widowed in 1881 when Jean died
                    aged 72, the cause of death given as bronchitis. Duncan Whyte himself died in
                    1897, having outlived his wife by nearly seventeen years, and his son-in-law
                    signed the death certificate. .</p>
                <p>Whyte clearly had no little success in his business, leaving behind accumulated
                    wealth of over £3,200 pounds, detailed along with his will in a lengthy Sheriff
                    Court record of 1898.</p>
